passages.text: On Tuesday, CPKC announced it has no interest in immediate M&A, and CEO Keith Creel noted it is firmly opposed to a transcontinental merger. Mr. Creel emphasized major rail mergers (as well as inevitable follow- on consolidation) poses unprecedented risks, and noted the potential benefits in support of transcon mergers can already be achieved through partnerships among railways (such as the network alliance between CPKC and CSX in the Southeast and recent Intermodal services announced by BNSF and CSX). However, Mr. Creel believes a transcon merger would result in a wave of mergers, suggesting CPKC could potentially be an active participant in M&A if a transcon merger were to transpire. Warren Buffet also noted Berkshire Hathaway (which owns BNSF Railway) is not interested in buying a railroad on Tuesday. Buffet and Greg Abel met with CSX CEO Joseph Hinrichs in Omaha on August 3 without any advisors, Reuters reported. CSX shares fell \(- 1.2\%\) on Tuesday (vs. S&P500's \(+0.4\%\) ) and are down \(- 9.3\%\) since last Thursday (vs. S&P's \(1.8\%\) gain), as event driven fund managers sold out. Focus for CSX shifts back to its fundamentals, particularly to mid- 4Q when the Howard Street tunnel and Blueridge Subdivision expenses end, and onto 2026 growth potential.

Less- than- Truckload (LTL) carriers XPO, SAIA, ODFL, and ARCB are set to post mid- 3Q updates next week (note we are hosting a call with ODFL's CFO on Wed post its 3Q update release). LTL stocks have remained under pressure (down \(19.4\%\) YTD vs S&P \(500^{\circ}s + 10.2\%\) ) given the muted industrial economy. For mid- quarter updates, the softness of July likely continued into August (as indicated by our bi- weekly Truck Shipper Survey), while commentary could suggest improving outlooks if the Fed cuts interest rates in mid- September. XPO noted July tons/day were down \(8\%\) year- year, slightly better than normal seasonality compared to June (it did not provide shipments or weight/shipment for July at that time). XPO also noted it faces easier comps in 3Q, so it expects full 3Q tons/day to be down less on a year- year basis than July (we target Jul/Aug/Sep tons/day of \(- 8\% / - 5\% / - 3.4\%\) ). It set a target for its operating ratio to remain flat 2Q- 3Q, outperforming normal seasonal deterioration of 200- 250 bps (we forecast \(82.8\%\) a 10 bps improvement). SAIA noted July- to- date tons/day were flat and shipments/day were down \(2.25\%\) y- y (we target J/A/S tons/day of \(- 1\% / - 1.5\% / - 2\%\) ). It targets 100 bps margin deterioration 2Q- 3Q (we expect \(88.8\%\) or 100 bps worse), on the low end of its 100- 200 bps normal seasonal deterioration. CEO Fritz Holzgrefe emphasized its view includes a wide range of variables (including volumes, timing of a \(- 75\) bps wage increase, and ongoing linehaul optimization; look for more detail on its wage timing). ODFL noted July month- to- date revenue/day was down \(5.1\%\) , with LTL tons/day down \(8.5\%\) y- y (we target J/A/S tons/day of \(- 8.3\% / - 3\% / - 2\%\) ). It targets yield ex- fuel to be up \(4\% - 4.5\%\) in 3Q, and for its 2Q- 3Q operating ratio to be 80- 120 bps worse sequentially, worse than normal seasonal trend of flat- 50 bps worse (we forecast \(75.5\%\) , a 90 bps deterioration). ODFL noted normal seasonality is typically based on sequential revenue growth of \(3\%\) , yet it expects revenue/day to remain flatish in 3Q (like in 2Q). (Cont'd on p3)...

Title: Subtitle  CSX: BNSF agreement does not pull M&A off table  Trucking: Survey Says: Moving up into August end; Demand (56.4) rises  Transport Tracker: Issue #1191, week ending Aug. 20, 2025
Ken Hoexter 25 August 2025  Ken Hoexter 22 August 2025  Ken Hoexter 21 August 2025

BNSF and CSX launched new intermodal service agreements to improve shipments between the western and eastern United States. The addition of new Intermodal services, operational by mid- September, will add direct domestic coast- to- coast services between Southern California and Charlotte, NC (using CSX's double stack capability at the Howard Street tunnel), and Jacksonville, FL. A new service will be launched between Phoenix, AZ and Atlanta, GA, aiming to convert over- the- road freight to rail through seamless service (eliminating rubber tire interchanges), and new direct international service between the Port of NY/NJ and Norfolk, VA and Kansas City.

FedEx Corp. nominated Richard Smith, chief operating officer for FedEx Express International and airline operations, and son of the company's late founder, Fred Smith, to the company's board of directors.
J.B. Hunt Transport Services named Brad Delco, SVP of Finance, as CFO and EVP of Finance. Former CFO John Kuhlow, will remain with the company as Chief Accounting Officer,

Union Pacific added 15 new Focus Sites across eight states to its network, with 12 of those sites located on short line railroads. Focus Sites are large- scale development sites suited for custom- built warehouses or industrial facilities and are railroad hubs where Union Pacific can concentrate resources, manage logistics, and provide targeted services for its customers.

C.H. Robinson Worldwide launched its Always- on Logistics Planner, a premium service experience powered by a digital workforce of AI agents who automate routine tasks, surface strategic insights, and enable seamless global coordination across every mode and region.

Separately, Henry 'Jay' Winship resigned from the Board effective immediately. The Company's 8- K filing noted the resignation was not due to a disagreement on any matter relating to the company's operations, policies, or practices.

**UPS** outsourced its proprietary weather-forecasting operations to the Weather Co., the owner of the Weather Channel, as it seeks to cut costs and streamline its business. The company has also shifted its technology support functions to third-party tech vendors.

**Key Takeaways - Up 6.5% (from -1.3% last week):** Total carloads for Week 34 of 2025 were up 6.5% year-year, to 619,860 (BNSF has not reported yet), reversing last week's 1.3% decrease (or 615,279 carloads). Carloads was up for the 9th week over the last 10, while growth was well above the past 10-week average of +1.4%. This quarter (3Q25) compares with a 2.5% uptick in 3Q24 (ex-BNSF). Coal increased (+13.2% year-year) for the 26th time over the last 27 weeks, improving from last week's 11.9% increase. Nat Gas prices were down 2% to $2.72/MMBtu from $2.77/MMBtu last week.Coal's absolute level of carloads were 62k, flat with 62k last week, and the 10-week avg of 57k. Chemical volumes were up 9.3% year-year, accelerating from last week's 0.3% increase. Grain (+14.2%) was up for the 20th time over the last 22 weeks, reversing last week's 5.8% downtick. Petroleum (+15.9%) was up, reversing last week's 3.5% downtick. Intermodal (+5.9%) increased, reversing last week's 1.2% downtick, while absolute volumes were 295k, just above last week's 294k, and the 287k past 10-week avg. Auto (+4.8%) was up for the 12th consecutive week, improving from last week's 1.3% increase.

**Overall** **Carloads**: Week 34 carloads were up 6.5% year-year, as increases at CN (+31.4%), CPKC (+28.2%), and NS (+1.3%), more than offset decreases at CSX (-0.1%) and UP (-3.9%). Quarter-to-date, carloads are up 2.4% year-year, as all rails are up, led by: CPKC (+5.4%), CN (+5.2%), UP (+2.5%), CSX (+0.5%), and NS (+0.3%). The 3Q25 carload trend of +2.4% is in line with our +2.3% full quarter target for the Class I rails on average (BNSF and NSC not incl.). The avg. carrier is trending above our target (+110 bps), with CNI the best at +460 bps vs. our tgt. (+5.2% vs. our +0.6%), vs CPKC the worst at -120 bps (+5.4% vs. our +6.6%).
**Revenue** **Ton** **Miles**: Week 34 RTMs: CN's RTMs are down 0.2% y-y 3QTD (vs. BofA -1.5% target). CPKC's RTM are up 4.4% y-y 3QTD (vs. BofA +6.7% target).

**Specifics: Intermodal carloads (47.7% of total)** were up 5.9% year-year, as increases at CN (+62.0%), CPKC (+28.7%), and CSX (+0.8%), more than offset decreases at NS (-0.5%) and UP (-10.5%). **Coal** **carloads** **(10.0% of total)** were up 13.2% year-year, as all rails increased, led by: CPKC (+52.0%), CN (+38.7%), CSX (+8.0%), UP (+2.5%), and NS (+0.5%). **Chemical** **carloads** **(9.3% of total)** were up 9.3% year-year, as increases at CPKC (+58.4%), CN (+30.6%), and UP (+3.9%), more than offset decreases at NS (-3.8%), and CSX (-12.8%). **Grain** **carloads** **(3.3% of total)** were up 14.2% year-year, as increases at CN (+39.8%), CPKC (+26.4%), and UP (+24.4%), more than offset decreases at NS (-11.0%), and CSX (-17.2%). **Petroleum** **carloads** **(3.6% of total)** were up 15.9% year-year, as increases at NS (+33.2%), CN (+29.9%), CPKC (+21.7%), and UP (+2.2%),more than offset a decrease at CSX (-6.9%). **Auto** **carloads** **(5.4% of total)** were up 4.8% year-year, as increases at CPKC (+20.5%), CN (+10.7%), NS (+8.0%), and CSX (+2.0%), more than offset a decline at UP (-4.5%).

This week, our proprietary bi- weekly BofA Truckload Demand Indicator for shippers' 0- to 3- month freight demand outlook increased to 56.4, from 51.7 last survey. The move seems to be based on increased confidence ahead of the Fed's potential rate cut in September, and the return of some demand as tariff rates become more settled. The Demand Indicator rose above the 54.2 average of the prior 3 Freight Recessions ('12, '15, and '19), and remains above 50 for the 8th consecutive issue. However, the Demand Indicator level remains somewhat muted, as it is still below a 60 'growth' signal for the 88th consecutive issue (since April 2022). The Demand Indicator is up 9% yr- yr. Rail carloads decreased 1.3% y- y this week. DAT Dry van spot linehaul rates rose slightly to \(\) 1.51\(/mile this week compared to\) \ \(1.50 / mi\) last week.

Of the respondents, 33% had positive short- term demand outlooks, up from 28% last issue, neutral outlooks were 54%, up from 47% last issue, and negative outlooks were 13%, down from 26% last issue. In the week of August 21, we surveyed 39 shippers for views on truckload demand, supply, pricing, and inventory levels.

The Inventory Indicator increased to 53.8, from 52.3 last issue, as inventory views remain elevated on soft demand. The Truck Capacity Indicator, or shippers' views of available capacity, decreased to 51.3, from 52.3 last issue, as additional bankruptcies continue to remove excess capacity. The Rate Indicator, or shippers' view on truck rates, decreased significantly to 52.6, from 59.3 last issue.
